<BaseLayout
  title="Contact | severancepayestimator.com"
  description="Contact the SeveranceCalc editorial team with questions, corrections, or partnership inquiries."
>
  <h1>Contact</h1>

  <p>
    Email <a href="mailto:hey@theclicklab.agency">hey@theclicklab.agency</a>. We're a small team, so email is the only channel we monitor &mdash; there's no live chat or phone line. If you've just received a severance offer, that's by design: this kind of question deserves a considered written answer, not a rushed one.
  </p>

  <h2>What we respond to</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Corrections to benchmark data, formulas, or citations.</strong> Our industry benchmarks come from BLS, SHRM, and WorldatWork surveys that get updated periodically. If a page cites a figure that's out of date, tell us which page and what the correct figure is; we verify against the primary source before making any change.</li>
    <li><strong>Errors or unclear language in guides.</strong> If a sentence in a guide is ambiguous, contradicts itself, or is just hard to follow, we want to know &mdash; plain language is one of our core editorial standards.</li>
    <li><strong>Suggestions for new content.</strong> If you searched for a severance-related question and couldn't find it on the Site &mdash; a specific industry, a specific state's WARN Act rules, a scenario the calculator doesn't handle &mdash; let us know what you were trying to figure out.</li>
    <li><strong>Press and business inquiries.</strong> Journalists covering layoffs and workplace issues, and businesses interested in advertising, can reach the same address.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What to expect</h2>
  <p>
    We read every message. Corrections and editorial questions typically get a reply within a couple of business days. If a correction is verified, we update the affected page and note the date of the material change, consistent with our <a href="/editorial/">corrections policy</a>. We don't always reply to content suggestions individually, but we do track them for future guides.
  </p>

  <h2>What we don't respond to</h2>
  <p>
    We can't evaluate your specific severance offer, tell you whether a release of claims is too broad, estimate exactly what your package should be, or review your separation agreement clause by clause &mdash; that requires an employment attorney who has actually read the document. We also don't recommend specific attorneys or law firms, don't negotiate on anyone's behalf, and don't accept payment to feature or promote anyone on the Site. If you email us asking for offer-specific advice, we'll point you back to this policy and to the guidance below on finding an attorney.
  </p>

  <h2>Before you email</h2>
  <p>
    Many questions we get are already answered on the Site: check the <a href="/faq/">FAQ</a> for common questions on severance formulas, timing, and taxation, or the <a href="/guides/">guides</a> &mdash; including <a href="/guides/how-to-negotiate-severance/">how to negotiate your severance package</a>, <a href="/guides/severance-pay-tax-guide/">how severance pay is taxed</a>, <a href="/guides/warn-act-severance-guide/">WARN Act severance</a>, and <a href="/guides/what-to-do-before-signing-severance/">what to do before signing a severance agreement</a>. If your question is about how the calculator arrived at a number, the <a href="/methodology/">methodology page</a> walks through the formula and benchmark data in detail.
  </p>

  <h2>If you're deciding whether to get an attorney involved</h2>
  <p>
    We don't make referrals, but a few things are worth knowing before you sign anything. A severance offer almost always comes with a release of claims &mdash; language where you give up the right to sue over your termination in exchange for the payment &mdash; and the scope of that release is exactly the kind of thing a generic benchmark can't evaluate. An employment attorney reviewing your specific agreement can tell you whether the release is standard or unusually broad, whether a non-compete or non-disparagement clause is enforceable in your state, and whether the number on the table reflects real negotiating room. If you're 40 or older, federal law (the Older Workers Benefit Protection Act) requires that an agreement give you at least 21 days to consider it individually (45 days for group layoffs) and a 7-day window to revoke your signature after signing &mdash; don't let anyone rush you past those windows. Most employment attorneys offer a flat-fee or free initial review specifically for severance agreements, so cost is rarely a reason to skip that step. If you'd rather start from a neutral referral source, your state bar association's lawyer referral service can point you to employment attorneys in your area.
  </p>
</BaseLayout>
